    "narrative": "The offensive engine for Ghost Ride the WHIP relies heavily on **James Wood** and **Austin Riley** today, our only two starters breaking the 65-point threshold. **James Wood** (69.33) is our strongest play, benefiting from a prime leadoff spot against a favorable matchup with Elder. His projection is bolstered by an aggressive +10% order bonus and the ability to leverage his elite speed, which remains our primary focus in this 5x5 format. Similarly, **Austin Riley** (72.25) finds himself in a high-leverage spot; he faces a soft matchup against Jake Irvin, where a 19% SP skill advantage significantly inflates his base expectations. These two anchors provide the safest paths to R and RBI, buffering us against potential volatility in the middle of the order.\n\nWhile we are optimized for efficiency, the bench decision regarding **Kyle Karros** (44.18) was the most contentious cut. **Kyle Karros** hovered near the marginal threshold due to a park boost, but he ultimately lost out to the lineup depth of **Tyler Soderstrom**, whose projected involvement against the vulnerable Emerson Hancock provides a higher ceiling for home run production. Meanwhile, we must exercise caution with **Mickey Moniak** (48.48) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (55.86); **Mickey Moniak** is fighting a severe -15% platoon disadvantage against the left-handed Justin Wrobleski, and **Vinnie Pasquantino** is facing an elite arm in Kyle Bradish, whose low xERA drags down his total score. \n\nFinally, with **Corbin Carroll**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Jose Caballero** all idle due to team off-days, our bench utility is strictly limited. We are monitoring **Dalton Rushing**, **Alex Freeland**, and **Max Muncy** closely as their lineup spots are pending; any drop in their batting order could necessitate a reshuffle, as their individual scores are already hovering in the marginal 57-60 range. We are essentially riding our projected starters to maximize our game caps, banking on the high-contact upside of **James Wood** and the power profile of **Austin Riley** to carry the category weight while our depth pieces like **Josh Naylor** and **Seiya Suzuki** navigate tougher matchups against Nola and Ginn.",
